Just a small issue with the init.d scripts.  They try to remount the /system filesystem in rw mode to update the cpu_protection file, however this fails on my Sensation as the script refers to the device /dev/block/mtdblock3 whereas on my sensation the filesystem is /dev/block/mmcblk0p22  The lines in the init.d script should be changed from ..  mount -o remount,rw /dev/block/mtdblock3 /system to.. mount -o remount,rw /system  This should work for all later versions of android..    cheers.  Oh and to the person wanting 'Advanced Task Killer' you need to go do some reading/learning :)  any kind of task killer that is not the native process management system is bad .. VERY BAD .. as it can lead to far higher CPU and battery consumption due to forcing persistent process to respawn every time it tries to kill them...

column1: Chromecast Support and Reliable Operation Please
column2: Very disappointed with the performance of this app when trying to use it on our Samsung DVD player!  Have been trying to 'catch up' the 'Safe House' series - missed the first episode - but just keep on experiencing the same problem after only a few minutes viewing, it being reported as follows:-  'There was a problem accessing the required content.  Please try again [SAMITV - 105.5]'  We have over the years deliberately bought Samsung equipment as the reports are that it always offers the best selection and operation of available apps, but it certainly isn't the case when it comes to your 'ITV Player'.  You probably won't like reading this, but you could learn a lot from the implementation of the 'BBC iPlayer' app, as that works without fail on our Samsung equipment.  PLEASE sort this out, AND get up to date by offering 'Chromecast' support for the app as well......BBC have!  'BTsport' app also works fine and supports 'Chromecast'.  Yesterday we also tried several times to watch the 'British Superbikes' from 22nd April, but encountered the same problem.  The 'BSB' from the 5th April did however work okay.  Not a very good success rate - 1 out of 3, I think you'd agree!

column1: File loading is novel, but ultimately useless.
column2: The file loader this app uses is interesting and novel, however it completely ignores directory sorting of ROMs. It also uses the internal ROM header name, which means that revisions and sometimes ROMs for other countries cannot be distinguished from each other. It also causes problems with Japanese ROMs, or any ROM that does not have a proper title in it's header (particularly homebrew/public domain ROMs.) The box art is also frequently missing or incorrect. This makes the app essentially unusable. An option to use a standard file chooser would earn this app five stars, but as it stands, it barely deserves two. Full disclosure: I have ceased using this app in preference to Snes9x EX+.

column1: Massive slowdown after 4.4 update on Nexus 7
column2: Tablet received OTA update to 4.4 (Kit Kat) and now this app runs extremely slow, cuts out sound often. Turbo does not solve issue. Had to look for alternative and found SNES9x ( that and ZSNES are/were 2 good emulators for the PC); free and includes save states. Please update your app for 4.4.

column1: File picker interesting but ultimately useless.
column2: The file loader this app uses is interesting and novel, however it completely ignores directory sorting of ROMs. It also uses the internal ROM header name, which means that revisions and sometimes ROMs for other countries cannot be distinguished from each other. It also causes problems with Japanese ROMs, or any ROM that does not have a proper title in it's header (particularly homebrew/public domain ROMs.) The box art is also frequently missing or incorrect. This makes the app essentially unusable. An option to use a standard file chooser would earn this app five stars, but as it stands, it barely deserves two. Unadvertised limitations in free version (no SRAM support) make it completely useless, as games cannot be saved in any manner (savestates are also a premium feature.) One extra star deducted. Full disclosure: I have ceased using this app in preference to Snes9x EX+.

I hope future versions will allow for USB audio as an option for karaoke singers and jam-track guitarists to be able to mix themselves in with their tracks for a truly portable online performance studio.  I would pay for such a thing.

This calculator has a strange user experience. For example, after pressing = the next digit will *append* to the previous result rather than clearing and starting a new input. Thus the button sequence 5 * 35 = 4 * 17 = does not result in 175 then 68. Instead it results in 175 then 29818 (that is, 175 then 1754 * 17 = 29818.)  So if you are used to other calculators, you need to learn to use clear after each = result with this calculator when you want to start a new calculation. This behavior may be OK once you get used to it, but again it is different from just about any calculator I've ever used. This is why I only rated this a 3 - I think it degrades from usability.  I discovered that a long press on the 'C' (clear) button will clear the entire display, and a quick click on 'C' will only remove one digit. It's also a little strange (to me) that pressing 'C' once will also remove a digit from a *result*, so be careful - you can alter a result without realizing it.  Unlike other calculators for Android Wear, 1/3*3 results in 1, not 0.999999.  I would prefer to see multiplication represented with the standard 'X' button label, not '*'.
Vulnerability: The software comes pre-configured with a default login of User: root Password: abc123. This weak password would easily be guessed leading to root compromise of the android system.

I liked this game, it's fun, challenging and rather enjoyable to play, IN THE EARLY STAGES.  As you progress through the Story Quest, the challenges gets harder and harder, until a point where Kabam! forces you to spend real-world money on the game in order to rank up your characters to such a degree that you can progress further into the game.  However, the more money you spend, the more expensive the game seems to get. Kabam! loves money, YOUR MONEY, and will do anything to get you to spend it.  I spent nearly 2000ZAR which is a ridiculous amount of money, on credits used to buy gold crystals, so I can upgrade and rank, and nearly every time I get a maximum of 3k gold out of 10 crystals bought for 200 credits, and then you spend 1000 credits on 10 premium crystals only to be given 2 star champions in every single one of them, making you spend more and more on credits in the quest to find a suitable character to progress further through the game.  I would recommend this game to any one out there wanting a short term adventure, playing with Marvel characters, but you would better spend your salary buying Marvel comics, preserving them and selling them in 5 years. Kabam is a joke!

I loved this app on iOS, so was thrilled to find it on Android. I use it mainly to study Japanese, and with Android's ability to use multiple keyboards, this app truly shines. I use the mazec3 keyboard,  which recognizes Japanese (and other) handwritten input. By using the 'spelling' feature,  I can literally write the answers,  helping me learn kanji and vocabulary simultaneously.  (This was simply not possible on iOS, making me delighted I switched to Android.) The TTS system provides a convenient 'hint' system. This app is incredibly well designed,  and can be as simple or complex as you want - perfect for ANY user.  EDIT: A belated thanks for adding multi-window support for Samsung devices. Except for the occasional crash, it's a brilliant flashcard companion for the AEDICT3 dictionary.

Interesting features: 1. allows vector graphics and text; 2. text can be entered as handwriting when used with mazec3; 3. eraser applies to vector graphics but not text. Together, these allow one to create elegant-looking handwritten documents such as TODO lists that, thanks to the difference in text and graphics layer, can be extremely easy to annotate and alter.

column1: Laggy, slow, and unpredictable. Huge potential though, thanks Sony!
column2: Just finished testing the app with my Smartwatch 2 and QX100.  The app is moving in the right direction and has a handful of features that many people will find useful. There's a shutter timer for 2 seconds or 10 seconds, but that has to be manually set from the smartphone itself for every capture. Clicking on the app from the smartwatch will open the app from the smartphone, and from there it will try to automatically connect with the camera, but that feature is a bit unpredictable at the moment. You can preview your view finder to post your shots, but that is also laggy.  One thing I do like about the camera is that it's able to capture pictures even when the smartphone's screen is off. I guess that saves some battery for you to capture even more photos on the go.  Hopefully Sony continues developing this app further because it has huge potential. I tried an app from a third party developer called 'Sony Cam Smartwatch Control', and found the experience horrible, and the rude developer was no help. I complained about the lack of features, and the developer rudely commented back to my review by saying I should learn how to read the feature list.

Prerequisites : * You need to be able to browse your phone. -Install an application like Astro File Manager. * You need the name of the wifi network your are connected. -Use Setting, click on Wireless and Networks and then on Wifi. You see an icon on the left of the wifi you use.  Start the ftp server on your android * The first time you will be able to configure the server and later you have to click on setting to do the same. -Enter -a user name like your first name. -a password. -a port (an integer) greater than 1024 and I have used 10021. -a directory on your android and I have used /mnt/sdcard/tmp (you can browse if you click). -click on restrict access to enforce maximum security. -Wakeup on comman (was selected for me). -Refresh media after transfer  (was selected for me). -Then choose the network name you have identified in the prerequisites. -Then click on save and restart.  From your personal computer (I use ubuntu). -Install filezilla (free application to access a ftp server). -Enter the ip (is display on the android), the port, username and password that you have used.  Enjoy !  -Rudy-

column1: Great... still needs a few tweaks!
column2: I discovered this game (for Windows) about 15 years ago?!... and have enjoyed it, despite changes that took things away - although good things were added, too! Dan... you need a detailed help file, and to think like someone who does not know how the controls work.... when writing the help file AND the tutorial.  There also needs to be a 'private-match' multi player option, so invites can be sent to a friend.  Also... I'd like to see a version for the Xbox 360 (arcade or indie), but based on WarPath 97 / 21stCentury version!

First order of business...I prefer paid games over free games...I like the instant gratification that can only be obtained from binge playing! Besides if you want to play for free, try My Forged Wedding PARTY :)  My invite code is vcy20i1....It gets me sweet images...  I have played several Voltage Inc games, and MFW is one of my absolute favorites! I usually stick to one character (it feels like cheating otherwise), but that was not the case with this game! Each character has their own well defined personalities, so I bought Yamato, Ren, and Kyoichi, and I loved all three. The characters are likable, each with their own quirks. My absolute favorite was Kyoichi, and I did not expect him to be my favorite. But he easily supplanted Yamato, with his sadistic, but sweet personality. You really feel like he cares for the MC, but is genuinely confused on how to express himself. But when he opens up...WOW! (BEST PROPOSAL EVER!!!) The gameplay was easy, and the plot was enjoyable. I definitely recommend this for fans of Voltage Inc.!

column1: Fair Warning - Does not provide Real Time Stats
column2: UPDATE: I replaced this device with OBDLink LX for 2/3rds the price.  Not only is OBDLink LX cheaper, it also offers up many times the amount of information that Automatic offers AND it includes real time stats like MPG.  I learned more about my car in a 10 minute test drive with OBDLink LX than I did in 16 months of using Automatic. Frankly I feel ripped off by Automatic.  -- previous review I bought two of these. The expectation was that I would be able to see real time data (specifically, I wanted to see instantaneous miles per gallon) with the expectation that immediate feedback from an app such as this would help me to improve my gas mileage.  YES... the app does what it says it does.  And for the most part it works fine.  (I have had some connectivity issues in the past, but updates to the app appear to have solved those)  So my specific problem is that I've had this for almost a year.  And for almost a year I've seen updates in the forums saying they were considering real time statistics.  But even as of today, it's still not a priority for them.    All I'm saying is, if you're expecting real time data - look elsewhere.

Gauges have inflexible scales, with grid lines at 11,22,33... instead 10,20,...   This is fixed in Torque Pro. which is more flexible with min, max, lo, high settings.  Given that this app is recommended for testing if your OBD2 Bluetooth device and car will talk to Torque, it should have guided you through connecting to the Bluetooth device.  Instead it doesn't give you any guidance that you need to go to Menu, More, Settings, Connection, before you can do anything useful.  It would be better to have an app that has the same OBD Bluetooth adapter code as Torque Pro, with the sole purpose of testing the OBD link..

Overpromise, underdeliver. If you seek a babysitter to track where you drove and when, this app and dongle might be for you. But know that you sacrifice your OBD port to get it. If you already use an OBD2 app like Torque Pro, you're likely to toss this Automatic rubbish into the bin within one week. Automatic suggests they have similar diagnostic displays, but it just doesn't work. period. Pay all you like for suggested 3rd party apps which purport to link thru Automatic, displaying OBD detail (That would be DashCommand, TouchScan...) But in the end, you'll realize you gave up real instruments for a trip tracker that doesn't really *need* OBD: Your phone can do all this trip tracking on its own.  Automatic? Meh! Anyone want to buy a pre-owned Automatic dongle cheap?

column1: Much to love, but MUCH work to do...
column2: JAPANESE STUDENTS-THIS SHOULD BE THE FIRST APP YOU INSTALL (along with Aedict3)!! But the interface needs a refresh.  ___Positives are:___+ Japanese recognition is excellent.  + lets you enter & edit text BEFORE inserting it into the document (unlike Samsung & Stylus Beta, which just dump it in after a set time).  + You can register certain strokes to match specific characters or phrases.  + auto-learning for results can be disabled so you can use it for flashcards without giving away the answer. (Wish this were a per-language setting, though.) + English input is OK (cursive is surprisingly better than manuscript). ___Negatives are:___- TINY Space Bar (why!?) - When using punctuation (parentheses, 'quotes', etc...) auto spacing fails. - Some suggested input for English is bizarre (random capital letters & frequent whargarble). - Switching between languages should only take one tap,  either through a 'globe' icon or, better yet, by exposing the 'settings' sub-option buttons (numbers, letters, symbols, language) on the top menu.  - NEEDS a button to hide the input area.___ That said, Mazec remains THE Android gold-standard for inputting handwritten Japanese.
